Hi Saurav, Hi &quot;hyysguyang&quot;,

On 7/30/07, hyysguyang &lt;hyysguyang@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;
&gt; --- In junit@yahoogroups.com, &quot;sauravkr&quot; &lt;sauravkr@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; I expect another annotation in apart from @before and @After that is
&gt;  &gt; @Finally. That should behave like finally and can be used for
&gt;  valuable
&gt;  &gt; work like closing file or IO in case of exception has occurred.
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; Also, I want some annotation instead of @beforeClass which can be
&gt;  &gt; applied for non static method and called only once as Constructors
&gt;  &gt; are called in normal java.
&gt;
&gt;  If you want some method called only once as Constructors are you can
&gt;  try the instantial blok statement.
&gt;  e.g:
&gt;  public class Person(){
&gt;  private String name;
&gt;
&gt;  {
&gt;  initName();
&gt;  }
&gt;
&gt;  public void initName(){this.name=&quot;init name...&quot;;}
&gt;  }

I would recommend avoiding using the initialization block for any test
setup/teardown because it is not guaranteed that the same instance of
a test class is going to be reused throughout all tests.

Go with @Before/@After instead.

Lasse

